The goal of our project - given descriptive parameters, predict the price of a house. We use data from a Kaggle competition "House Prices: Advanced Regression techniques": a modernized and expanded version of the often cited Boston Housing dataset. Let's explore the data first.

To understand variables that are connected to the price of sale the most, let's plot 5 of them with largest correlaton with SalePrice.

In [10]:
#saleprice correlation matrix
k = 5 #number of variables for heatmap
cols = corrmat.nlargest(k, 'SalePrice')['SalePrice'].index
cm = np.corrcoef(train_data[cols].values.T)
sns.set(font_scale=1.25)
# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.zeros_like(cm, dtype=np.bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

hm = sns.heatmap(cm, mask=mask, cbar=True, annot=True, square=True, fmt='.2f', annot_kws={'size': 10}, yticklabels=cols.values, xticklabels=cols.values, cmap='Blues')
plt.show()

The results are not surprising: the better is the quality of the house, the bigger living area is, the more place there is in the garage, the more expensive the house is.

Let's visualize the distribution of these important variables with respect to SalePrice.¶

In [11]:

It can be seen that all houses without garage are cheaper than 200 000, and then the price generally increases with increasing garage area. Though, we noticed some outliars, with huge garage area, but low price.

The boxplot of GarageCars looks interesting - seems that data is not very centered around the mean(there are a lot of cars on the whiskers), and prices of houses with 4 places for cars are simmilar to those with 2 cars. These could include same houses who were outliars in the previous plot.

Of course, number of cars in garage are strongly correlated with size of a garage(0.88), so let's take a look at how they correspond to each other.

There are 19 columns with missing data. When looking closely, it doesn't seem that they are very important when deciding on buying a house - Pool, MiscFeature, Fireplace Quality, type of masonry(really?).

Then, there is a lot of missing data for information on a garage, but the most important information about garage is conveyed in GarageCars and GarageArea variables. Same with basement - there is a variable BasementTotalSF, which is intuitively more important than FinType or Exposure, and strongly correlated with all of them. So,if ve delete these variables, will we miss them? We don't think so. Finally, column "Electrical" has missing value in only 1 observation, so we'll delete this observation and keep the variable.

In [17]:
train_data = train_data.drop((missing_data[missing_data['Total'] > 1]).index,1)
train_data = train_data.drop(train_data.loc[train_data['Electrical'].isnull()].index)

Out liars!¶

Now,we need to look for outliars and treat them how they deserve to be treated, because thay can effect the quality of our models. To identify them, we'll first standardize the data, making its mean equal to 0 and variance equal to 1.

In search for normality¶

We remember that distribution of SalePrice is skewed to the right. Lets see how far away it is from the normal.
In [25]:
#histogram
sns.distplot(train_data['SalePrice'], color='#0abde3', fit = norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(train_data['SalePrice'], plot=plt)

Ok, 'SalePrice' is not normal. It shows 'peakedness', positive skewness and does not follow the diagonal line. To "make things normal", we'll use log transformation. Plots below illustrate the transformed data, which is much closer to normall distribution.

In [26]:
#applying log transformation
train_data['SalePrice'] = np.log(train_data['SalePrice'])
In [27]:
#transformed histogram and normal probability plot
sns.distplot(train_data['SalePrice'], fit=norm,  color='#0abde3');
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(train_data['SalePrice'], plot=plt)

Now, let's check the distribution of GrLivingArea.

In [28]:
#histogram
sns.distplot(train_data['GrLivArea'], color='#0abde3', fit = norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(train_data['SalePrice'], plot=plt)

Tastes like skewness...let's apply the powerful spell again. Avada Kedavra!(Log Transformation)

In [29]:
train_data['GrLivArea'] = np.log(train_data['GrLivArea'])
In [30]:
#transformed histogram and normal probability plot
sns.distplot(train_data['GrLivArea'], fit=norm, color='#0abde3');
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(train_data['GrLivArea'], plot=plt)

Distribution and probability plot of transformed data are perfectly normal now.

Time for models!¶

We decided to start with the most simple approach - linear model, that will include all of our columns.

In [32]:

It's a failure again - R^2 of 100%? :( The model is overfitted, so let's move on to smarter approaches!¶

Ridge regression¶

One way to avoid overfitteng is to use Ridge regression. With just a small bias of estimation in train data, we can better the estimation of test data and minimize Variance, as well as provide better long-term predictions. BAM! Ridge regression minimizes sum of squared residuals + alpha*(all_coefficient_slopes^2).

In [39]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, RidgeCV, ElasticNet, LassoCV, LassoLarsCV
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

df = train_data
X =df.loc[:, df.columns != 'SalePrice']
Y = df['SalePrice']

def rmse_cv(model):
    rmse= np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(model, X, Y, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv = 5))
    return(rmse)

model_ridge = Ridge()

alphas = [0.05, 0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 5, 10, 15, 30, 50, 75]
cv_ridge = [rmse_cv(Ridge(alpha = alpha)).mean() 
            for alpha in alphas]

Using cross-validation, we can see, that rmse is minimized when the index of of alpha is:

Lasso regression - more exciting results!¶

The main difference from Ridge regression is, that we minimize ssr + alpha* ABSOLUTE VALUE of all coefficient slopes. When Ridge can make the slope of silly parameters only assimptotically close to zero, Lasso can ACTUALLY make them zero. THis is useful in our case, when we are not sure whether all the variables in our dataset significantly influence price.

In [44]:
alphas = [1, 0.1, 0.001, 0.0005]

cv_lasso = [rmse_cv(LassoCV(alphas = alphas)).mean() 
            for alpha in alphas]

model_lasso = LassoCV(alphas = alphas).fit(X, Y)

Choosing alpha that minimizes penalty function (ssr + alpha* ABSOLUTE VALUE of all coefficient slopes):

Now, we want to work with test data. And here comes trouble. Rememeber, we cleaned our data? Now, we have to make sure to have the same columns in test data to fit in the trained xgboost model. Also, we need to play around to make categorical ('dummy') variables the same. The NAs in test data we replace with median values, since we cannot delete them, as we need price estimation for each house.
